<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n54130d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54130d">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54130d"> 130(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> O shipshaped phrase / drumlooking words <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54130d"><li>FW 128.06 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/lexfa.htm#n54130d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/l39fa.htm#n54130d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54130d">MS BL 47476a-218</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:459 <a name="fad8" href="../../ff/fdra/fda.htm#fad8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fa/fad8.htm#n54130d">Draft: I.6&sect;1.8</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><i>Ornements du son</i>: ce sont ceux qui dispara&icirc;traient si l&apos;on rempla&ccedil;ait les mots qui les portent par d&apos;autres mots synonymes (aussi le <cite>S.D.</cite> y comprend-il &agrave; juste titre les &laquo;ornements mixtes&raquo;, du son et du sens, d&eacute;crits par certains auteurs). Les principaux sont l&apos;allit&eacute;ration, la rime, le jeu de mots, le double sens (double sens du vocable, qui doit, ne l&apos;oublions pas, se r&eacute;soudre en un sens unique du mot; autrement, c&apos;est &laquo;ambigu&iuml;t&eacute;&raquo;, qui est une faute). On cite pour m&eacute;moire, comme amusements tr&egrave;s inf&eacute;rieurs, <mark>les arrangements de lettres dont la transcription graphique reproduit le dessin</mark> &laquo;d&apos;un lotus, d&apos;un sabre, d&apos;un <mark>tambour</mark>, d&apos;une roue, d&apos;un jet d&apos;urine de vache&raquo;, etc. &mdash; l&apos;ornement &eacute;tant toujours, cependant, pour l&apos;oreille. Les ornements du son doivent &ecirc;tre soumis aux lois de correspondances entre phon&egrave;mes et saveurs. <br>[Ornaments of sound: these are the ones that would disappear if the words carrying them were replaced by other synonymous words (so the SD rightly includes "mixed ornaments", sound and of meaning, described by some authors). The main ones are alliteration, rhyme, pun, double meaning (double meaning of the word, which must, let us not forget, be resolved in a single sense of the word; otherwise, it is "ambiguity", which is a fault). As a very inferior amusement, we cite as arrangements the letters, the graphic transcription of which reproduces the drawing "of a lotus, a saber, a drum, a wheel, a jet of urine from cow ", etc. - the ornament being always, however, for the ear. The ornaments of sound must be subject to the laws of correspondence between phonemes and flavors. <small> Ren&eacute; Daumal, <a name="RDLP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RDLP"><cite title="source">Les pouvoirs de la parole</cite></a> (1938) [74-5]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
